@<html><head>
<link rel="stylesheet" href="mh.css" type="text/css"/>
</head><body>

<ul>
<h3>Why use Mozharness?</h3>

<ul><p>
With a good deal of generalization:
</p></ul>

<center>
<table border="1" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr>
<th>Problem</th><th>Individual scripts</th><th>Mozharness scripts</th>
</tr><tr><td>
Learning curve
  </td><td>
<center>X</center>
  </td><td>
&nbsp;
</td></tr><tr><td>
Sharing code
  </td><td>
&nbsp;
  </td><td>
<center>X</center>
</td></tr><tr><td>
Familiarity between scripts, both for devs and users
  </td><td>
&nbsp;
  </td><td>
<center>X</center>
</td></tr><tr><td>
Intricate configuration management
  </td><td>
&nbsp;
  </td><td>
<center>X</center>
</td></tr><tr><td>
Full logging
  </td><td>
&nbsp;
  </td><td>
<center>X</center>
</td></tr><tr><td>
Built in error parsing
  </td><td>
&nbsp;
  </td><td>
<center>X</center>
</td></tr><tr><td>
Usable in many different contexts
  </td><td>
&nbsp;
  </td><td>
<center>X</center>
</td></tr></table>
</center>

<br />

<ul><li>
Allows for shared scripts between various platforms, products, branches in production; also between production and developers.
</li><li>
Makes us less dependent on buildbot.
</li><li>
Once we get over the learning curve and we get a critical mass of knowledge + shared code, development will be faster.
</li></ul>

<p>
<a href="03-config.html">config --&gt;</a><br />
</p>

</body></html>
